ich are fervently discussed and debated via websites, online forums, videos, and novels. By exploring the worldview of peakists, and the unexpected way that the fear of peak oil and climate change transformed many members of this left-leaning group into survivalists, Schneider-Mayerson builds a larger analysis of the rise of libertarianism, the role of oil in modern life, the political impact of digital technologies, the racial and gender dynamics of post-apocalyptic fantasies, and the social organization of environmental denial.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmentalism. 0aHubbert peak theoryxPolitical aspects. 0aHubbert peak theoryxSocial aspects. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexIndustrial capacityxForecasting. 70(DE-601)1047666380(DE-588)4139144-5aErdölgewinnung2gnd 70(DE-601)1060796970(DE-588)4077587-2aSozialer Wandel2gnd 70(DE-601)1061349650(DE-588)4061644-7aUmweltschutz2gnd 70(DE-601)2338265560(DE-588)4467522-7aMaximum2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aenvironmentalism, environment, libertarianism, libertarian, political science, politics, cultural studies, social sciences, environmental study, oil production, global, worldwide, international, transnational, postcarbon future, ideology, subculture, masculinity, gender, hubbert peak theory, petroleum, scarcity, race, industry, business, trade, forecasting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022628526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226285573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226285573/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles